versity (57.4%), The University of Sydney (50.8%), RMIT University (50.0%) — against a national median of 28.0% across institutions. A change to student visa settings lands hardest here.","view":"exposure"},{"severity":"alert","title":"Domestic drop-out rates vary more than fourfold","body":"Torrens University Australia (27.4%) sit at more than double the national median of 12.7%. These are sector attrition rates, so students who transferred to another university are not counted as lost.","view":"rankings"},{"severity":"warn","title":"Students per academic staff member differ sharply","body":"Victoria University (35.6 students per academic FTE), RMIT University (32.8 students per academic FTE), Macquarie University (28.1 students per academic FTE) carry the heaviest loads, against a median of 22.0. The ratio counts casual academic staff, so it understates how many students share a continuing teacher.","view":"rankings"},{"severity":"info","title":"The four-year completion rate is the most misread number in higher education","body":"Only 41.5% of domestic bachelor students had completed four years after starting (2021-2024) — but 35.5% were still enrolled, because many degrees run longer than four years. Given nine years (2016-2024), 70.5% have completed. \"Most students don't finish\" is an artefact of the short window.","view":"outcomes"},{"severity":"alert","title":"ATAR still predicts completion nine years later","body":"93.7% of school leavers admitted with an ATAR of 95-100 had completed a bachelor degree within nine years, against 55.0% of those in the 30-49 band — a gap of 38.7 percentage points that the four-year view understates.","view":"outcomes"},{"severity":"info","title":"Graduate output is diverging between institutions","body":"Torrens University Australia has grown completions the fastest (83 to 5,688, +6753%), while Charles Sturt University has fallen the furthest (9,263 to 7,451, -20%).","view":"trends"}]}